



48-Hour AI Agents Hackathon
Building Practical, Ethical AI Agents for People, Work, and Society
1. Overview
This 48-hour hackathon challenges teams to design and build AI agents—task-oriented systems that combine rules, data, and AI reasoning to support real-world decision-making.
The focus is not on AI demos but on usable agents with clear roles, constraints, and explainability. All projects must align with real societal needs and map to the UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs).
Teams will also package their work for inclusion in a shared AI Agent Marketplace, creating a lasting post-hackathon asset.
2. Team Composition
4–5 members per team
Each team must include at least one apprentice from a different cohort
3. Hackathon Theme: AI Agents in the Real World
An AI agent is a system that:
Accepts structured or unstructured inputs
Reasons over goals, constraints, and context
Produces recommendations, decisions, or actions
Explains why outputs were generated
Important: AI must be a component of a system—not the entire system.
4. Tracks & Challenge Areas
TRACK 1: Personal & Self‑Improvement Agents
SDGs: 3, 4, 5, 10
Challenge Statement
Build an AI agent that helps individuals improve learning, finances, or personal decision-making—safely and ethically.
Example Agent Ideas
Personal budgeting or financial planning agent
AI teaching assistant for students
Career or skills-pathway advisor
Wellness or habit-support agent (non-medical)
Minimum Technical Requirements
Stateful logic (profiles, sessions, or memory)
Prompt engineering with constraints
Guardrails (disclaimers, refusal logic, safety checks)
Clear system architecture
Stretch (Bonus)
Confidence or risk scoring
Long-term conversation memory
Goal or progress tracking
TRACK 2: Business & Process Improvement Agents
SDGs: 1, 8, 9
Challenge Statement
Build an AI agent that supports businesses or organisations in making better operational or economic decisions.
Example Agent Ideas
Tax or compliance assistant
Digital marketing or content-planning agent
Micro‑business viability or pricing agent
Workflow or process-optimisation agent
Minimum Technical Requirements
Scoring or ranking logic
Structured outputs (JSON, tables, reports)
Explainability layer
Error handling and validation
Stretch (Bonus)
Bias detection or mitigation
Alternative scoring strategies
Multi‑user or multi‑business comparisons
TRACK 3: Social, Cultural & Community Agents
SDGs: 2, 6, 11, 12, 13, 15
Challenge Statement
Build an AI agent that supports safer, more inclusive, or more sustainable communities without heavy simulations or over‑engineering.
Example Agent Ideas
Community security or safety advisory agent
Environmental monitoring or reporting agent
Tourism or cultural recommendation agent
Public‑service navigation agent
Minimum Technical Requirements
Rule‑based logic combined with AI reasoning
Domain constraints (location, season, regulations)
Multi‑step decision logic
Stretch (Bonus)
Scenario simulations
Confidence or uncertainty scoring
Transparent assumptions and limitations
5. AI Agent Marketplace (Post‑Hackathon Output)
All teams must prepare their agents for inclusion in a shared AI Agent Marketplace.
Each submission must include:
Agent name and description
Problem solved and target user
Input/output schema
Working demo (CLI or UI)
Deployment or usage instructions
6. Cross‑Hackathon Rules (Mandatory)
All teams must deliver:
A working demo (CLI or simple UI)
Clear system architecture
AI used as a component, not the entire app
A README covering:
Problem statement
SDG alignment
Architecture and design choices
AI usage
Trade‑offs and limitations
7. Allowed Technology
Python, Go, JavaScript
REST APIs
LLMs, embeddings, vector search
Rule engines
Simple ML models (optional)
